# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: araucaria-bidwillii
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/abies] The wood of firs is used for pulp to make paper, for plywood, and for indoor construction.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/abies] Some species serve as Christmas trees, while others are used as decorative trees with their brightly coloured cones.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/abies] In art, Lucas Cranach the Elder painted *Madonna under the fir tree* for Wrocław Cathedral in 1510.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/abies] The English name "fir" derives from the Old Norse *fyri* or the Old Danish *fyr*.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/abies] The generic name *Abies* is the Latin for "fir".
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/abies] Fir trees are tall, often 40–60 metres and sometimes approaching 100 metres high, usually with a single straight trunk.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/abies] The crown starts conical, but becomes more varied in shape with age.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/abies] The primary branches are arranged in whorls around the trunk.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/abies] Firs have needle-like leaves, arranged spirally but often appearing to be in two or more rows on opposite sides of the twigs.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/abies] The base of each leaf is round and attached to a small pit in the twig.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/abies] Each leaf is normally twisted at its base so that the side with stomata faces downwards.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/abies] In the upper crown on cone-bearing branches, the leaves are shorter, curved, and sometimes sharp.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/abies] Firs differ from other conifers such as spruces in having erect, cylindrical female seed cones 5–25 cm (2–10 in) long that disintegrate at maturity to release the winged seeds.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/abies] Seed cones take a year to become mature; they start out green or other bright colour, darkening as they develop to dark brown or black.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/abies] The leaflike seed bracts are visible when young, and in some species remain so.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/abies] The seeds sit in thin cups; each seed has a triangle-shaped wing.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/abies] The male cones are pendulous (dangling) and resemble catkins; both pollen and seeds are wind-dispersed.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/abies] The oldest pollen assignable to the genus dates to the Late Cretaceous in Siberia, with records of leaves and reproductive organs across the Northern Hemisphere from the Eocene onwards.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/abies] Based on transcriptome analysis, *Keteleeria* is sister to *Abies*, with the Pseudolariceae the next nearest relatives.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/abies] In 1754, Philip Miller set up the genus *Abies*; he also defined the type species *Abies alba*.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/abies] In 1878, George Engelmann classified only a part of the genus; Heinrich Mayr did the same in 1890, as did the German botanist Wilhelm Patschke in 1913.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/abies] The classifications by Paul Robert Hickel in 1906 to 1908, and by P.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/abies] Landry in 1984, made use only of a subset of the available morphological characteristics.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/abies] In 1990 and 2001, the Dutch botanist Aljos Farjon attempted a more complete classification; he accepted 48 species within the genus; in 2017 he reduced this to 46.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/abies] Adopting a different approach, in 2011 Z.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/abies] Rácz treated the genus as containing 67 species.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/abies] As of September 2025, Plants of the World Online accepted 49 species.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/abies] Section *Abies* is found in central, south, and eastern Europe and Asia Minor.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/abies] Section *Balsamea* is found in northern Asia and North America, and high mountains further south.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/abies] Section *Grandis* is found in western North America to Mexico, Guatemala, Honduras and El Salvador, in lowlands in the north, moderate altitudes in south.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/abies] Section *Momi* is found in east and central Asia and the Himalaya, generally at low to moderate altitudes.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/abies] Section *Amabilis* is found in the Pacific Coast mountains in North America and Japan, in high rainfall areas.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/abies] Section *Pseudopicea* is found in the Sino – Himalayan mountains at high altitudes.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/abies] Section *Oiamel* is found in central Mexico at high altitudes.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/abies] Firs are distributed around the Northern Hemisphere.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/abies] The genus is native across much of North America, Eurasia, Turkey, Syria, Morocco, and Algeria.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/abies] It is introduced in Scandinavia and the British Isles.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/abies] *Abies sibirica* grows as far north as 67°N in Siberia, while *A. guatemalensis* grows as far south as 15°N in Central America.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/abies] Most firs favour cold climates, whether at altitude in mountain ranges or at high latitude.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/abies] Many species have relict distributions, occupying small areas of what were once much larger distributions.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/abies] Firs are hosts to a variety of invertebrate pests and fungal diseases.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/abies] Pest groups include adelgid bugs, aphids, bark beetles, clearwing moths, conifer twig weevils, caterpillars of some moths, nematodes, sawflies, spider mites, and spittlebugs.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/abies] Diseases of firs include annosus (*Heterobasidion*) root rot, cankers, and needle cast.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/abies] Unlike the Douglas fir (*Pseudotsuga*), firs produce softwood, often used as pulp or for the manufacture of plywood and rough timber.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/abies] It is commonly used in Canadian Lumber Standard graded wood, used for internal stud walls and similar applications.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/abies] *Abies spectabilis* is used in Ayurveda as an antitussive (cough suppressant) drug.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/abies] Firs produce a variety of terpenoids that could have practical uses.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/abies] Terpenoid composition of the bark varies by genetics, geography, age and size of the tree.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/abies] Caucasian fir, noble fir, Fraser's fir and balsam fir are popular Christmas trees, generally considered to be the best for this purpose, with aromatic foliage that does not shed many needles on drying out.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/abies] Many form decorative garden trees, notably Korean fir and Fraser's fir, which produce brightly coloured cones even when very young, still only 1–2 m (3 ft 3 in – 6 ft 7 in) tall.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/abies] Many fir species are grown in botanic gardens and other specialist tree collections in Europe and North America.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/abies] Lucas Cranach the Elder painted *Madonna under the fir tree* for Wrocław Cathedral in 1510.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/abies] The painting was taken to Germany after the Second World War for restoration, but a copy was made and substituted for the original.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/abies] The forgery was discovered, partly because the copy was on a fir board where the original was on lime wood.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/abies] The original was returned to Poland in 2012, the most valuable painting to be restituted to the country.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Over 300 languages, as well as sign languages, and other groupings have developed a wide range of individual cultures.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Aboriginal art has existed for thousands of years and ranges from ancient rock art to modern watercolour landscapes.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Traditional Aboriginal music developed a number of unique instruments, and contemporary Aboriginal music spans many genres.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Aboriginal peoples did not develop a system of writing before colonisation.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Cultural traditions and beliefs as well as historical tellings of actual events are passed down in Aboriginal oral tradition, also known loosely as oral history (although the latter has a more specific definition).
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Some of the stories are many thousands of years old.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] In a study published in February 2020, new evidence produced using radiometric dating showed that both Budj Bim and Tower Hill volcanoes erupted at least 34,000 years ago.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Significantly, this is a "minimum age constraint for human presence in Victoria", and also could be interpreted as evidence for the Gunditjmara oral histories which tell of volcanic eruptions being some of the oldest oral traditions in existence.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] An axe found underneath volcanic ash in 1947 was also proof that humans inhabited the region before the eruption of Tower Hill.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Australian Aboriginal art has a history spanning thousands of years.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Aboriginal artists continue these traditions using both modern and traditional materials in their artworks.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Aboriginal art is the most internationally recognizable form of Australian art.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Several styles of Aboriginal art have developed in modern times including the watercolour paintings of Albert Namatjira, the Hermannsburg School, and the acrylic Papunya Tula "dot art" movement.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Painting is a large source of income for some Central Australian communities such as at Yuendumu.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Basket weaving has been traditionally practised by the women of many Aboriginal peoples across the continent for centuries.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] For many Aboriginal cultures, the night sky is a repository of stories and law.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Songlines can be traced through the sky and the land.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Stories and songs associated with the sky under many cultural tents.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Aboriginal Australians' oral tradition and spiritual values build on reverence for the land and on a belief in the Dreamtime, or Dreaming.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] The Dreaming is considered to be both the ancient time of creation and the present-day reality of Dreaming.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] It describes the Aboriginal cosmology, and includes the ancestral stories about the supernatural creator-beings and how they created places.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Each story can be called a "Dreaming", with the whole continent criss-crossed by Dreamings or ancestral tracks, also represented by songlines.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] There are many different groups, each with their own individual culture, belief structure and language.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] To Aboriginal people, some places are sacred, owing to their central place in the mythology of the local people.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] The words "law" and "lore" are commonly used interchangeably: "law" was introduced by the British, whereas "lore" relates to the customs and stories from the Dreamtime, which has been passed on through countless generations through songlines, stories and dance.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Learned from childhood, lore dictates the rules on how to interact with the land, kinship and community.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Kurdaitcha (or kurdaitcha man, and also spelled *kurdaitcha*, *gadaidja*, *cadiche*, *kadaitcha*, or *karadji*) is a type of shaman amongst the Arrernte people, an Aboriginal group in Central Australia.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] The kurdaitcha may be brought in to punish a guilty party by death.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] The word may also relate to the ritual in which the death is willed by the kurdaitcha man, known also as bone-pointing.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] The expectation that death would result from having a bone pointed at a victim is not without foundation.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Other similar rituals that cause death have been recorded around the world.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Victims become listless and apathetic, usually refusing food or water with death often occurring within days of being "cursed".
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] When victims survive, it is assumed that the ritual was faulty in its execution.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] The phenomenon is recognized as psychosomatic in that death is caused by an emotional response—often fear—to some suggested outside force and is known as "voodoo death".
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] As this term refers to a specific religion, the medical establishment has suggested that "self-willed death", or "bone-pointing syndrome" is more appropriate.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] In Australia, the practice is still common enough that hospitals and nursing staff are trained to manage illness caused by "bad spirits" and bone pointing.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] The complete system of Yolngu customary law is the "Madayin", which embodies the rights and responsibilities of the owners of the law, or citizens (*rom watangu walal*, or simply *rom*).
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Madayin includes the rom, as well as the objects that symbolise the law, oral rules, names and song cycles, and the sacred places that are used to maintain, develop and provide education in the law.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Rom can be roughly translated as "law" or "culture", but it embodies more than either of these words.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Galarrwuy Yunupingu has described *Rom watangu* as the overarching law of the land, which is "lasting and alive... my backbone".
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] It covers ownership of land and waters and the resources within this region; it controls production trade; and includes social, religious and ethical laws.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] These include laws for conservation and farming of flora and fauna.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Observance of Madayin creates a state of balance, peace and true justice, known as *Magaya*.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Rom includes bush crafts such as basket-weaving and mat-making, and stories which teach history, hunting, spear-making, gathering food, building shelters and rafts, various rituals, and taking care of others.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] "Rom" is a word and concept shared by at least one of the nearby peoples, the Anbarra, who also perform a Rom ceremony.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Ceremonies provide a time and place for everyone in the group and community to work together to ensure the ongoing survival of spiritual and cultural beliefs.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Certain stories are individually "owned" by a group, and in some cases dances, body decoration and symbols in a ceremony pass on these stories only within the group, so it is vital that these ceremonies are remembered and performed correctly.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Men and women have different roles, and are sometimes appointed as guardians of a sacred site, whose role it is to care for the site and the spiritual beings who live there, achieved partly by performing ceremonies.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] The terms “men’s business” and “women’s business” are sometimes used; neither have greater spiritual needs or responsibilities than the other, but jointly ensure that sacred practices are passed on.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Men often conduct ceremonies, but women are also guardians of special knowledge, hold great spiritual power within a group, and conduct ceremonies.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Participation in ceremonies can also be restricted by age, family group, language group, but are sometimes open to all, depending on the purpose of the ceremony.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Right of access to songs and dances pertaining to a specific ceremony belong to a certain defined group (known as manikay by the Yolngu peoples of north-east Arnhem Land, or clan songs); some may be shared with people outside the community, but some are never shared.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] There is a wide range of songs, dances, music, body ornamentation, costume, and symbolism, designed to connect the body with the spiritual world of the ancestors.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Ceremonies help to sustain Aboriginal identity as well as the group's connection to country and family.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] The didgeridoo originated in northern Australia, but is now used throughout the continent.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Clapsticks, seed rattles and objects such as rocks or pieces of wood are used; in a few areas, women play a drum made from goanna, snake, kangaroo or emu skin.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Animal native foods include kangaroo, emu, witchetty grubs and crocodile.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Plant foods include fruits such as quandong, kutjera, spices such as lemon myrtle and vegetables such as warrigal greens, bananas and various native yams.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Since the 1970s, there has been recognition of the nutritional and gourmet value of native foods by non-Indigenous Australians, and the bushfood industry has grown enormously.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Pituri is a mixture of leaves and wood ash traditionally chewed as a stimulant (or, after extended use, a depressant) by Aboriginal Australians widely across the continent.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Leaves are gathered from any of several species of native tobacco (*Nicotiana*) or from at least one distinct population of the species *Duboisia hopwoodii*.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Various species of *Acacia*, *Grevillea* and *Eucalyptus* are burned to produce the ash.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Traditional healers (known as Ngangkari in the Western jester areas of Central Australia) are highly respected men and women who not only acted as healers or doctors, but also generally served as custodians of important Dreaming stories.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] This "fire-stick farming", or "burning off", reduces the fuel-load for a potential major bush fire, while fertilising the ground and increasing the number of young plants, providing additional food for kangaroos and other fauna hunted for meat.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] It is regarded as good husbandry and "looking after the land" by Aboriginal people of the Northern Territory.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] The Australian Aboriginal languages consist of around 290–363 languages belonging to an estimated 28 language families and isolates, spoken by Aboriginal Australians of mainland Australia and a few nearby islands.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] The relationships between these languages are not clear at present.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Many Australian Aboriginal cultures have or traditionally had a manually coded language, a signed counterpart of their oral language.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] This appears to be connected with various speech taboos between certain kin or at particular times, such as during a mourning period for women or during initiation ceremonies for men.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Avoidance speech in Australian Aboriginal languages is closely tied to elaborate tribal kinship systems in which certain relatives are considered taboo.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Avoidance relations differ from tribe to tribe in terms of strictness and to whom they apply.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Typically, there is an avoidance relationship between a man and his mother-in-law, usually between a woman and her father-in-law, and sometimes between any person and their same-sex parent-in-law.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] For some tribes, avoidance relationships are extended to other family members, such as the mother-in-law's brother in Warlpiri or cross-cousins in Dyirbal.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] All relations are classificatory – more people may fall into the "mother-in-law" category than just a man's wife's mother.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Australian Aboriginal English (AAE) is a dialect of Australian English used by a large section of the Indigenous Australian (Aboriginal Australian and Torres Strait Islander) population.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Australian Kriol is an English-based creole language that developed from a pidgin used in the early days of European colonisation.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] The pidgin died out in most parts of the country, except in the Northern Territory, which has maintained a vibrant use of the language, spoken by about 30,000 people.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] It is distinct from Torres Strait Creole.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] At the point of the first colonisation, Indigenous Australians had not developed a system of writing, so the first literary accounts of Aboriginal people come from the journals of early European explorers, which contain descriptions of first contact.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] A letter to Governor Arthur Phillip written by Bennelong in 1796 is the first known work written in English by an Aboriginal person.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] The Yirrkala bark petitions of 1963 are the first traditional Aboriginal document recognised by the Australian Parliament.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Oodgeroo Noonuccal (1920–1993) was a famous Aboriginal poet, writer and rights activist credited with publishing the first Aboriginal book of verse: *We Are Going* (1964).
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Sally Morgan's 1987 memoir *My Place* brought Indigenous stories to wider notice.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Leading Aboriginal activists Marcia Langton (*First Australians* documentary TV series, 2008) and Noel Pearson (*Up from the Mission*, 2009) are contemporary contributors to Australian non-fiction.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Other voices of Indigenous Australians include the playwright Jack Davis and Kevin Gilbert.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Writers coming to prominence in the 21st century include Kim Scott, Alexis Wright, Kate Howarth, Tara June Winch, Yvette Holt and Anita Heiss.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Aboriginal people have developed unique musical instruments and folk styles.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] The didgeridoo is often considered the national instrument of Aboriginal Australians; however, it was traditionally played by peoples of Northern Australia, and only by the men.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] It has possibly been used by the people of the Kakadu region for 1500 years.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Clapping sticks are probably the more ubiquitous musical instrument, especially because they help maintain rhythm.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] More recently, Aboriginal musicians have branched into rock and roll, hip hop and reggae.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Bands such as No Fixed Address and Yothu Yindi were two of the earliest Aboriginal bands to gain a popular following among Australians of all cultures.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] In 1997 the State and Federal Governments set up the Aboriginal Centre for the Performing Arts (ACPA) to preserve and nurture Aboriginal music and talent across all styles and genres from traditional to contemporary.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Woggabaliri is a traditional Indigenous Australian "co-operative kicking volley game".
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] The Indigenous in areas of and near New South Wales played a ball game called Woggabaliri.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] The ball was usually made of possum fur, and was played in a group of four to six players in circle.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] It was a co-operative kicking game to see for how long the ball can be kept in the air before it touches the ground.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] The Djab Wurrung and Jardwadjali people of western Victoria once participated in the traditional game of Marn Grook, a type of football played with possum hide.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] The game is believed by some commentators, including Martin Flanagan, Jim Poulter and Col Hutchinson, to have inspired Tom Wills, inventor of the code of Australian rules football.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Similarity between Marn Grook and Australian football include jumping to catch the ball or high "marking", which results in a free kick.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Use of the word "mark" in the game may be influenced by the Marn Grook word *mumarki*, meaning "catch".
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] However, this is likely a false etymology; the term "mark" is traditionally used in Rugby and other games that predate AFL to describe a free kick resulting from a catch, in reference to the player making a mark on the ground from which to take a free kick, rather than continuing to play on.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] There are many Indigenous AFL players at professional level, with approximately one in ten players being of Indigenous origin as of 2007.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] The contribution of the Aboriginal people to the game is recognized by the annual AFL "Dreamtime at the 'G" match at the Melbourne Cricket Ground between Essendon and Richmond football clubs (the colors of the two clubs combine to form the colours of the Aboriginal flag).
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Testifying to this abundance of Indigenous talent, the Aboriginal All-Stars, an AFL-level all-Aboriginal football side competes against any one of the Australian Football League's current football teams in pre-season tests.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] The Clontarf Foundation and football academy is just one organisation aimed at further developing aboriginal football talent.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] The Tiwi Bombers began playing in the Northern Territory Football League and became the first all-Aboriginal side to compete in a major Australian competition.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Coreeda is a style of folk wrestling practiced in Australia and is based on Aboriginal combat sports that existed in the pre-colonial period before the 19th century.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] Combining the movements of the traditional kangaroo dance as a warm up ritual, with a style of wrestling that utilizes a yellow 4.5 meter diameter circle that has black and red borders (similar to the Aboriginal flag), Coreeda is often compared to sports as diverse as capoeira and sumo.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] A popular children's game in some parts of Australia is weet weet, or throwing the play stick.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aboriginal-ceremonies] The winner throws the weet weet furthest or the most accurately.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] The **acorn** is the nut of the oaks and their close relatives (genera *Quercus*, *Notholithocarpus* and *Lithocarpus*, in the family Fagaceae); alternatively known as **glans**.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] It usually contains a seedling surrounded by two cotyledons (seedling leaves), enclosed in a tough shell known as the pericarp, and borne in a cup-shaped cupule.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] Acorns take between 5 and 24 months (depending on the species) to mature; see the list of *Quercus* species for details of oak classification, in which acorn morphology and phenology are important factors.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] The word *acorn* (earlier *akerne*, and *acharn*) is related to the Gothic name *akran*, which had the sense of "fruit of the unenclosed land".
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] The word was applied to the most important forest produce, that of the oak.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] Chaucer spoke of "achornes of okes" in the 14th century.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] By degrees, popular etymology connected the word both with "corn" and "oak-horn", and the spelling changed accordingly.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] 15th–16th century) derives from association with *ac* (Old English: "oak") + *corn*.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] The Latin *glans* as found in many literature regarding it originally applies to any nut is the root of several Romance words for the acorn (the French *gland*, Catalan *gla*, Italian *ghianda*) cognate to Greek βάλανος, which also extends to the vascular penile tip from similarity in shape.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] Acorns play an important role in forest ecology when oaks are plentiful or dominant in the landscape.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] The volume of the acorn crop may vary widely, creating great abundance or great stress on the many animals dependent on acorns and the predators of those animals.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] Acorns, along with other nuts, are termed mast.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] Wildlife that consume acorns as an important part of their diets include birds, such as jays, pigeons, some ducks, and several species of woodpeckers.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] Small mammals that feed on acorns include mice, squirrels and several other rodents.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] One beetle species, *Thorectes lusitanicus*, also feeds on acorns.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] Acorns have a large influence on small rodents in their habitats, as large acorn yields help rodent populations to grow.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] Large mammals such as pigs, bears, and deer also consume large amounts of acorns; they may constitute up to 25% of the diet of deer in the autumn.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] In Spain, Portugal and the New Forest region of southern England, pigs are still turned loose in *dehesas* (large oak groves) in the autumn, to fill and fatten themselves on acorns.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] Heavy consumption of acorns can, on the other hand, be toxic to other animals that cannot detoxify their tannins, such as horses and cattle, especially if eaten in excess.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] The larvae of some moths and weevils also live in young acorns, consuming the kernels as they develop.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] Acorns are attractive to animals because they are large and thus efficiently consumed or cached.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] Percentages vary from species to species, but all acorns contain large amounts of protein, carbohydrates and fats, as well as the minerals calcium, phosphorus and potassium, and the vitamin niacin.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] Total food energy in an acorn also varies by species, but all compare well with other wild foods and with other nuts.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] Acorns also contain bitter tannins, the amount varying with the species.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] Since tannins, which are plant polyphenols, interfere with an animal's ability to metabolize protein, creatures must adapt in different ways to use the nutritional value acorns contain.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] Animals may preferentially select acorns that contain fewer tannins.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] When the tannins are metabolized in cattle, the tannic acid produced can cause ulceration and kidney failure.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] Animals that cache acorns, such as jays and squirrels, may wait to consume some of these acorns until sufficient groundwater has percolated through them to leach out the tannins.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] Other animals buffer their acorn diet with other foods.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] Many insects, birds, and mammals metabolize tannins with fewer ill effects than do humans.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] Species of acorn that contain large amounts of tannins are very bitter, astringent, and potentially irritating if eaten raw.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] This is particularly true of the acorns of American red oaks and English oaks.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] The acorns of white oaks, being much lower in tannins, are nutty in flavor; this characteristic is enhanced if the acorns are given a light roast before grinding.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] Tannins can be removed by soaking chopped acorns in several changes of water, until the water no longer turns brown.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] Cold water leaching can take several days, but three to four changes of boiling water can leach the tannins in under an hour.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] Hot water leaching (boiling) cooks the starch of the acorn, which would otherwise act like gluten in flour, helping it bind to itself.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] For this reason, if the acorns will be used to make flour, then cold water leaching is preferred.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] Being rich in fat, acorn flour can spoil or molder easily and must be carefully stored.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] Acorns are also sometimes prepared as a massage oil.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] Acorns of the white oak group, *Leucobalanus*, typically start rooting as soon as they are in contact with the soil (in the fall), then send up the leaf shoot in the spring.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] Acorns are too heavy for wind dispersal, so they require other ways to spread.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] Oaks therefore depend on biological seed dispersal agents to move the acorns beyond the mother tree and into a suitable area for germination (including access to adequate water, sunlight and soil nutrients), ideally a minimum of 20–30 m (70–100 ft) from the parent tree.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] Many animals eat unripe acorns on the tree or ripe acorns from the ground, with no reproductive benefit to the oak, but some animals, such as squirrels and jays serve as seed dispersal agents.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] Jays and squirrels that scatter-hoard acorns in caches for future use effectively plant acorns in a variety of locations in which it is possible for them to germinate and thrive.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] Even though jays and squirrels retain remarkably large mental maps of cache locations and return to eat them, the odd acorn may be lost, or a jay or squirrel may die before consuming all of its stores.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] A small number of acorns manage to germinate and survive, producing the next generation of oaks.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] Scatter-hoarding behavior depends on jays and squirrels associating with plants that provide good packets of food that are nutritionally valuable, but not too big for the dispersal agent to handle.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] The beak sizes of jays determine how large acorns may get before jays ignore them.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] Acorns germinate on different schedules, depending on their place in the oak family.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] Once acorns sprout, they are less nutritious, as the seed tissue converts to the indigestible lignins that form the root.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] In some cultures, acorns once constituted a dietary staple, though they have largely been replaced by grains and are now typically considered a relatively unimportant food, except in some Native American and Korean communities.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] Several cultures have devised traditional acorn-leaching methods, sometimes involving specialized tools, that were traditionally passed on to their children by word of mouth.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] Raw acorns are 28% water, 41% carbohydrates, 24% fat, and 6% protein (table).
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] In a reference amount of 100 g (3.5 oz), raw acorns supply 387 calories and are a rich source (20% or more of the Daily Value, DV) of vitamin B6, folate, copper, and manganese (table).
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] Acorns served an important role in early human history and were a source of food for many cultures around the world.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] Dental microwear suggests that Neanderthals in Belgium consumed acorns among other hard foods.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] Many modern human cultures relied on acorns, such as the Ancient Greek lower classes and the Japanese (during the Jōmon period), for instance.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] In antiquity, Pliny the Elder noted that acorn flour could be used to make bread.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] Acorns rarely form a large part of modern diets and are not currently cultivated on scales approaching that of many other nuts.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] However, if properly prepared (by selecting high-quality specimens and leaching out the bitter tannins in water), acorn meal can be used in some recipes calling for grain flours.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] Varieties of oak differ in the amount of tannin in their acorns.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] Varieties preferred by Native Americans, such as *Quercus kelloggii* (California black oak), may be easier to prepare or more palatable.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] Roasted acorn flour is a main ingredient in sweet cakes special to Kurdish areas of Iran and Iraq.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] Acorns are a traditional food of many indigenous peoples of North America, and long served an especially important role for Californian Native Americans, where the ranges of several species of oaks overlap, increasing the reliability of the resource.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] In the San Francisco Bay Area acorns found were often associated with grinding tools.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] Stone tools like hammerstone and anvil, millingstones, and mortar and pestle help crack open the acorn and grind the acorn into dust.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] Acorns and balanophagy (acorn-eating [fr]) were associated with ideas of primitive life and Arcadia in classical literature and beyond.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] A motif in Roman architecture, also popular in Celtic and Scandinavian art, the acorn symbol is used as an ornament on cutlery, furniture, and jewelry; it also appears on finials at Westminster Abbey.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] The acorn was used frequently by both Union and Confederate forces during the American Civil War.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] Modern US Army Cavalry Scout campaign hats still retain traces of the acorn today.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] The acorn is the symbol for the National Trails of England and Wales, and is used for the waymarks on these paths.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] The acorn, specifically that of the white oak, is also present in the symbol for the University of Connecticut.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/acorn] Acorns are also used as charges in heraldry.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aleurites-moluccanus] First described by Carl Linnaeus in 1753, the species' origin is unclear due to its spread by humans, but it can be found in many tropical rainforests and gallery forests.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aleurites-moluccanus] Various parts of the plant have regional or cultural uses.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aleurites-moluccanus] The candlenut tree grows to a height of up to 30 m (98 ft), with wide spreading or pendulous branches.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aleurites-moluccanus] The leaves are pale green, simple, and ovate or heart-shaped on mature shoots, but may be three-, five-, or seven-lobed on saplings.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aleurites-moluccanus] They are up to 20 cm (8 in) long and 13 cm (5 in) wide and young leaves are densely clothed in rusty or cream stellate hairs.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aleurites-moluccanus] Petioles measure up to 12.5 cm (5 in) long and stipules about 5 mm (1⁄4 in).
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aleurites-moluccanus] The flowers are small; male flowers measure around 5 mm in diameter, female flowers about 9 mm.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aleurites-moluccanus] The fruit is a drupe about 4–6 cm (1+1⁄2–2+1⁄4 in) in diameter with one or two lobes; each lobe has a single soft, white, oily kernel contained within a hard shell about 2 cm (3⁄4 in) in diameter.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aleurites-moluccanus] These nuts, upon germinating, produce cotyledons or seed leaves up to 9 cm (3.5 in) long by 5.5 cm (2.2 in) wide.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aleurites-moluccanus] This plant was first described by Carl Linnaeus in his *Species Plantarum* (1753) as *Jatropha moluccana*.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aleurites-moluccanus] It was renamed as *Aleurites moluccana* by Carl Ludwig Willdenow in an 1805 edition of *Species Plantarum*, but the ending was corrected to match the gender of the Latin genus *Aleurites moluccanus*.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aleurites-moluccanus] While there are many online references to the spelling "Aleurites moluccana", this is not accepted by botanical authorities such as the International Plant Names Index or the Germplasm Resources Information Network.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aleurites-moluccanus] The genus name derives from the Ancient Greek ἄλευρον (*áleuron*), meaning "flour" or "meal", and refers to the new growth which appears to be dusted with flour.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aleurites-moluccanus] The species epithet means "from the Moluccas".
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aleurites-moluccanus] Its native range is impossible to establish precisely because of early spread by humans, and the tree is now distributed throughout the New and Old World tropics including the Indian subcontinent, Southeast Asia, Papuasia, Queensland in Australia, and some islands of the western Pacific Ocean.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aleurites-moluccanus] The candlenut was first domesticated on the islands of Southeast Asia.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aleurites-moluccanus] Remains of harvested candlenuts have been recovered from archaeological sites in Timor and Morotai in eastern Indonesia, dated to around 13,000 and 11,000 BP, respectively.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aleurites-moluccanus] Archaeological evidence of candlenut cultivation is also found in Neolithic sites of the Toalean culture in southern Sulawesi dated to around 3,700 to 2,300 BP.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aleurites-moluccanus] Early Austronesian voyagers introduced candlenuts, as a canoe plant, widely across the Pacific islands; the trees became naturalized to high volcanic islands.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aleurites-moluccanus] In Australia the seeds are eaten by rodents, in particular the giant white-tailed rat.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aleurites-moluccanus] The broken shells of the fruits are often found underneath the trees.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aleurites-moluccanus] The larvae of the coleopteran *Agrianome fairmairei* feed on dead candlenut wood, and are considered a delicacy in New Caledonia.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aleurites-moluccanus] Because the seeds contain saponin, phorbol, and toxalbumins, they are mildly toxic when raw, inducing a laxative effect.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aleurites-moluccanus] Heat treatment reduces the toxicity of the protein component.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aleurites-moluccanus] While mildly toxic when raw, the nut is appreciated in many cultures once cooked or toasted.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aleurites-moluccanus] In Indonesian and Malaysian cuisine, it is commonly used in curries, and on the Indonesian island of Java, it is used to make a thick sauce that is eaten with vegetables and rice.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aleurites-moluccanus] A Hawaiian condiment known as *ʻinamona* is made from roasted kukui mixed into a paste with salt.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aleurites-moluccanus] *ʻInamona* is a key ingredient in traditional Hawaiian *poke*.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aleurites-moluccanus] The kernel is the source of candlenut oil, which has no known toxicity and is not an irritant, even to the eyes.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aleurites-moluccanus] In ancient Hawaiʻi, kukui fruits were burned to provide light.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aleurites-moluccanus] The nuts were strung in a row on a palm leaf midrib, lit on one end, and burned one by one every fifteen minutes or so.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aleurites-moluccanus] This led to their use as a measure of time.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aleurites-moluccanus] Hawaiians extracted the oil from the nut and burned it in a stone oil lamp called a *kukui hele po* (light, darkness goes) with a wick made of *kapa* cloth.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aleurites-moluccanus] A red-brown dye made from the inner bark was used on *kapa* and *aho* (*Touchardia latifolia* cordage).
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aleurites-moluccanus] A coating of kukui oil helped preserve *ʻupena* (fishing nets).
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aleurites-moluccanus] The *nohona waʻa* (seats) and *pale* (gunwales) of *waʻa* (outrigger canoes) were made from the wood.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aleurites-moluccanus] The trunk was sometimes used to make smaller canoes used for fishing.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aleurites-moluccanus] The oil can often be found in Indonesian hair-care products.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aleurites-moluccanus] In Fiji, where the nut is called *sikeci*, the oil is used in cosmetic products.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aleurites-moluccanus] Wealthier members of the Batak people have their coffins (Karo: *pelangkah*) made from the wood, carved in the shape of a boat whose bow is decorated with the carved head of a hornbill, a horse, or a mythical beast known as a singa.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aleurites-moluccanus] In the Philippines, the fruit and tree are traditionally known as *lumbang*, after which Lumban, a lakeshore town in Laguna province, is named.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aleurites-moluccanus] Before the intrusion of non-native species, it was frequently used as a property-line manager because its silvery underleaf makes the tree easy to distinguish from a distance.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aleurites-moluccanus] In the state of Sabah, Malaysian Borneo, the Dusun tribes call the fruit *godou* and use it in tattoo-making as an optional ingredient for the ink.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aleurites-moluccanus] As recently as 1993 on the outlying islands of the kingdom of Tonga, candlenuts were chewed into sweet-scented emollient used during a traditional funerary ritual.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aleurites-moluccanus] They were used for making various sweet-smelling oils for the skin.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aleurites-moluccanus] In Australia, Aboriginal Australians used them for a variety of similar purposes.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aleurites-moluccanus] In Flores near Ende, it is called *kéloré* and used as a mordant for dyes with *Morinda citrifolia* (*mengkudu*).
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aleurites-moluccanus] On the island of Rapa Iti in the Austral Islands, fish hooks were carved from the endocarp of the candlenut as a result of lacking other suitable material.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aleurites-moluccanus] These fish hooks were quite small and were used for catching certain species of fish, such as *Leptoscarus vaigiensis* (*Komokomo*) and *Stegastes fasciolatus* (*Nganga*).
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aleurites-moluccanus] The plant is also known by the common names **candleberry**, **Indian walnut**, ***kemiri***, **varnish tree**, ***nuez de la India***, ***buah keras***, ***godou***, **kukui tree**, and ***rata kekuna***.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aleurites-moluccanus] It became Proto-Eastern-Malayo-Polynesian and Proto-Oceanic **tuRi* which is then reduplicated.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aleurites-moluccanus] Modern cognates including Fijian, Tongan, Rarotongan, and Niue *tui-tui*; and Hawaiian *kui-kui* or *kukui*.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aleurites-moluccanus] The Malay language in both has another name given to the nut which is *buah keras* (literally "hard fruit").
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aleurites-moluccanus] In Uganda, the seed is referred to as *kabakanjagala*, meaning "the king loves me".
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aleurites-moluccanus] In Maui, the *kukui* is a symbol of enlightenment, protection, and peace.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aleurites-moluccanus] Kamapuaʻa, the hog-man fertility demigod, was said to be able to transform into a *kukui* tree.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aleurites-moluccanus] One of the legends told of Kamapuaʻa: one day, a man beat his wife to death and buried her beneath Kamapuaʻa while he was in tree form.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aleurites-moluccanus] *Kukui* was named the state tree of Hawaii on 1 May 1959 due to its multitude of uses.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/aleurites-moluccanus] It also represents the island of Molokaʻi, whose symbolic color is the silvery green of the *kukui* leaf.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] ***Prunus dulcis*** (Mill.) D.A.Webb, nom. illeg. non *Prunus dulcis* Rouchy) is a species of tree from the genus *Prunus*.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Along with the peach, it is classified in the subgenus *Amygdalus*, distinguished from the other subgenera by corrugations on the woody shell (endocarp) surrounding the seed.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] The fruit of the almond is a drupe, consisting of an outer hull and a hard shell with the seed, which is not a true nut.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] *Shelling* almonds refers to removing the shell to reveal the seed.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Blanched almonds are unshelled almonds that have been treated with hot water to soften the outer skin, which is then removed to reveal the white embryo.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Once almonds are cleaned and processed, they can be stored for around a year if kept refrigerated; at higher temperatures they will become rancid more quickly.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Almonds are used in many cuisines, often featuring prominently in desserts, such as marzipan.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] The almond tree prospers in a moderate Mediterranean climate with cool winter weather.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] It is rarely found wild in its original setting.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Almonds were one of the earliest domesticated fruit trees, due to the ability to produce quality offspring entirely from seed, without using suckers and cuttings.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Evidence of domesticated almonds in the Early Bronze Age has been found in the archeological sites of the Middle East, and subsequently across the Mediterranean region and similar arid climates with cool winters.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] California produces about 80% of the world's almond supply.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Due to high acreage and water demand for almond cultivation, and need for pesticides, California almond production may be unsustainable, especially during the persistent drought and heat from climate change in the 21st century.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Droughts in California have caused some producers to leave the industry, leading to lower supply and increased prices.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] The almond is a deciduous tree growing to 3–4.5 metres (10–15 feet) in height, with a trunk of up to 30 centimetres (12 inches) in diameter.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] The young twigs are green at first, becoming purplish where exposed to sunlight, then grey in their second year.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] The leaves are 8–13 cm (3–5 in) long, with a serrated margin and a 2.5 cm (1 in) petiole.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] The fragrant flowers are white to pale pink, 3–5 cm (1–2 in) diameter with five petals, produced singly or in pairs and appearing before the leaves in early spring.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Almond trees thrive in Mediterranean climates with warm, dry summers and mild, wet winters.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] The optimal temperature for their growth is between 15 and 30 °C (59 and 86 °F) and the tree buds have a chilling requirement of 200 to 700 hours below 7.2 °C (45.0 °F) to break dormancy.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Almonds begin bearing an economic crop in the third year after planting.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Trees reach full bearing five to six years after planting.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] The fruit matures in the autumn, 7–8 months after flowering.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] The outer covering, consisting of an outer exocarp, or skin, and mesocarp, or flesh, fleshy in other members of *Prunus* such as the plum and cherry, is instead a thick, leathery, grey-green coat (with a downy exterior), called the hull.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Inside the hull is a woody endocarp which forms a reticulated, hard shell (like the outside of a peach pit) called the pyrena.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Inside the shell is the edible seed, commonly called a nut.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Generally, one seed is present, but occasionally two occur.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] After the fruit matures, the hull splits and separates from the shell, and an abscission layer forms between the stem and the fruit so that the fruit can fall from the tree.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] During harvest, mechanised tree shakers are used to expedite fruits falling to the ground for collection.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] The almond was named *Amygdalus communis* by Carl Linnaeus in his Species plantarum in 1753.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] For the name 'Amygdalus' he referred to Gaspard Bauhin's *Pinax* (1623).
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] In 1801 the species was for the first time placed in the genus *Prunus* by August Batsch.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] In that genus, the name *Prunus communis* was no longer available because in 1778 William Hudson had already assigned it to a taxon in which he included the plum (*Prunus domestica*).
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Batsch thereupon named the species *Prunus amygdalus*, where 'amygdalus' is the old generic name and should therefore be treated as a noun in apposition.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Meanwhile, in 1768, Philip Miller had published the name of what he believed to be a second species of almond: *Amygdalus dulcis*.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] He mentioned Linnaeus' *Amygdalus communis* as the first species.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] It was not until 1967 that the combination *Prunus dulcis* was published for the almond by David Allardice Webb, on the assumption that *Amygdalus dulcis* was nothing more than a synonym of *Amygdalus communis*, and thus an available name for that species.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] The epithet *dulcis* (1768) is older than *amygdalus* (1801) and would therefore have priority.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Webb noted that it was unfortunate that a species known for 165 years as *Prunus amygdalus* now had to be renamed under the rules of nomenclature.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] However, it later turned out that in 1967 the name *Prunus dulcis* was no longer available for the almond because it had already been used for a cherry in an 1878 publication by L'Abbé Rouchy.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] The oldest valid combination in *Prunus* is therefore *Prunus amygdalus*.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] *dulcis* are predominantly sweet but some individual trees produce seeds that are somewhat more bitter.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] The genetic basis for bitterness involves a single gene, the bitter flavour furthermore being recessive, both aspects making this trait easier to domesticate.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] *amara* are always bitter, as are the kernels from other species of genus *Prunus*, such as apricot, peach and cherry (although to a lesser extent).
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] The bitter almond is slightly broader and shorter than the sweet almond and contains about 50% of the fixed oil that occurs in sweet almonds.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] It contains the enzyme emulsin which, in the presence of water, acts on the two soluble glucosides amygdalin and prunasin yielding glucose, cyanide and the essential oil of bitter almonds, which is nearly pure benzaldehyde, the chemical causing the bitter flavour.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Bitter almonds may yield 4–9 milligrams of hydrogen cyanide per almond and contain 42 times higher amounts of cyanide than the trace levels found in sweet almonds.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] The origin of cyanide content in bitter almonds is via the enzymatic hydrolysis of amygdalin.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] P450 monooxygenases are involved in the amygdalin biosynthetic pathway.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] A point mutation in a bHLH transcription factor prevents transcription of the two cytochrome P450 genes, resulting in the sweet kernel trait.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] The word *almond* is a loanword from Old French *almande* or *alemande*, descended from Late Latin *amandula*, *amindula*, modified from Classical Latin *amygdala*, which is in turn borrowed from Ancient Greek *amygdálē* (ἀμυγδάλη) (cf. amygdala, an almond-shaped portion of the brain).
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Late Old English had *amygdales* 'almonds'.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] The adjective *amygdaloid* (literally 'like an almond, almond-like') is used to describe objects which are roughly almond-shaped, particularly a shape which is part way between a triangle and an ellipse.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] For example, the amygdala of the brain uses a direct borrowing of the Greek term *amygdalē*.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] The precise origin of the almond is controversial due to estimates for its emergence across wide geographic regions.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Sources indicate that its origins were in an area stretching across Central Asia, Iran, Turkmenistan, Tajikistan, Kurdistan, Afghanistan, and Iraq, or in an eastern Asian subregion between Mongolia and Uzbekistan.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] In other assessments, both botanical and archaeological evidence indicates that almonds originated and were first cultivated in West Asia, particularly in countries of the Levant.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Most recent sources specified Iran and Anatolia (present day Turkey) as origin locations of the almond, with Iran as the main origin centre.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] The wild form of domesticated almond grew in parts of the Levant.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Almond cultivation was spread by humans centuries ago along the shores of the Mediterranean Sea into northern Africa and southern Europe, and more recently to other world regions, notably California.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Selection of the sweet type from the many bitter types in the wild marked the beginning of almond domestication.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] The wild ancestor of the almond used to breed the domesticated species is unknown.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] The species *Prunus fenzliana* may be the most likely wild ancestor of the almond, in part because it is native to Armenia and western Azerbaijan, where it was apparently domesticated.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Wild almond species were grown by early farmers, "at first unintentionally in the garbage heaps, and later intentionally in their orchards".
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Almonds were one of the earliest domesticated fruit trees owing to their ability to be grown from seed, allowing their cultivation to have perhaps predated the advent of grafting.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Domesticated almonds appear in the Early Bronze Age (3000–2000 BCE), such as the archaeological sites of Numeira (Jordan), or possibly earlier.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] They were found in Tutankhamun's tomb in Egypt (c.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] 1325 BCE), probably imported from the Levant.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Ibn al-'Awwam's 12th-century *Book on Agriculture* includes an article on almond tree cultivation in Spain.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Of the European countries that the Royal Botanic Garden Edinburgh reported as cultivating almonds, Germany is the northernmost, though the domesticated form can be found as far north as Iceland.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Almond trees are small to medium-sized but commercial cultivars can be grafted onto a different root-stock to produce smaller trees.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Breeding programs have found a high shell-seal trait, which reduces insect damage and mold contamination.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] The most widely planted varieties of almond are self-incompatible; hence these trees require pollen from a tree with different genetic characters to produce seeds.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Almond orchards therefore must grow mixtures of almond varieties.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] In addition, the pollen is transferred from flower to flower by insects; therefore commercial growers must ensure there are enough insects to perform this task.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] The large scale of almond production in the U.S. creates a significant problem of providing enough pollinating insects.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Additional pollinating insects are therefore brought to the trees.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] The pollination of California's almonds is the largest annual managed pollination event in the world, with over 1 million hives (nearly half of all beehives in the U.S.) being brought to the almond orchards each February.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Much of the supply of bees is managed by pollination brokers, who contract with migratory beekeepers from at least 49 states for the event.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] This business was heavily affected by colony collapse disorder at the turn of the 21st century, causing a nationwide shortage of honey bees and increasing the price of insect pollination.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] To partially protect almond growers from these costs, researchers at the Agricultural Research Service, part of the United States Department of Agriculture (USDA), developed self-pollinating almond trees that combine this character with quality characters such as a flavour and yield.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Almond trees can be attacked by an array of damaging microbes, fungal pathogens, plant viruses, and bacteria.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Pavement ants (*Tetramorium caespitum*), southern fire ants (*Solenopsis xyloni*), and thief ants (*Solenopsis molesta*) are seed predators.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] *Bryobia rubrioculus* mites are most known for their damage to this crop.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Almond production in California is concentrated mainly in the Central Valley, where the mild climate, rich soil, abundant sunshine and water supply make for ideal growing conditions.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Due to the persistent droughts in California in the early 21st century, it became more difficult to raise almonds in a sustainable manner.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] The issue is complex because of the high amount of water needed to produce almonds: a single almond requires roughly 1.1 US gallons (0.92 imperial gallons; 4.2 litres) of water to grow properly.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Regulations related to water supplies are changing so some growers have destroyed their current almond orchards to replace with either younger trees or a different crop such as pistachio that needs less water.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] California almond farmers have promoted growing use of sustainable farming practices, including introduction of water-efficient irrigation technology, funding of honeybee health research, and productively using waste biomass (such as shells) in pursuit of a zero waste industry.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] In 2023, world production of almonds was 3.5 million tonnes, led by the United States with 51% of the total, followed by Spain and Australia as secondary producers (table).
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Australia is the largest almond production region in the Southern Hemisphere.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Most of the country's almond orchards are located along the Murray River corridor in New South Wales, Victoria, or South Australia.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] In the Australian financial year 1 July 2024–30 June 2025, the national almond crop fell 5%, but increased in value by 20%, to a record A$1.3 billion.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] India was the second-largest export market, at 19,803 t (19,490 long tons; 21,829 short tons), a tonnage similar to that of the previous financial year.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] As of late February 2026, Australia was forecast to harvest a record almond crop of 167,000 t (164,000 long tons; 184,000 short tons) in the 2025–26 financial year.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Spain has diverse commercial cultivars of almonds grown in Catalonia, Valencia, Murcia, Andalusia, and Aragón regions, and the Balearic Islands.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] The almond cultivar 'Marcona' is unique, having a kernel that is short, round, relatively sweet, and delicate in texture; it is marketed by name.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Its origin is unknown, but has been grown in Spain over centuries.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] In the U.S., production is concentrated in California where 400,000 ha (1,000,000 acres) and six different almond varieties were under cultivation in 2017, with a yield of 2.25 billion pounds (1.02 billion kilograms) of shelled almonds.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] California production is marked by a period of intense pollination during late winter by rented commercial bees transported by truck across the U.S. to almond groves, requiring more than half of the total U.S. commercial honeybee population.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] The value of total U.S. exports of shelled almonds in 2016 was $3.2 billion.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] All commercially grown almonds sold as food in the U.S. are sweet cultivars.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Food and Drug Administration reported in 2010 that some fractions of imported sweet almonds were contaminated with bitter almonds, which contain cyanide.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Bitter almonds contain some 40 times the trace levels of cyanide found in sweet almonds.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Extract of bitter almond was once used medicinally, but even in small doses, its effects are severe or lethal, especially in children; the cyanide must be removed before consumption.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] The acute oral lethal dose of cyanide for adult humans is reported to be 0.5–3.5 mg/kg (0.2–1.6 mg/lb) of body weight (approximately 50 bitter almonds for the average adult), so that for children consuming 5–10 bitter almonds may be fatal.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Symptoms of eating such almonds include vertigo and other typical cyanide poisoning effects.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Almonds may cause allergy or intolerance.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Cross-reactivity is common with peach allergens (lipid transfer proteins) and tree nut allergens.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Symptoms range from local signs and symptoms (e.g., oral allergy syndrome, contact urticaria) to systemic signs and symptoms including anaphylaxis (e.g., urticaria, angioedema, gastrointestinal and respiratory symptoms).
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Almonds are susceptible to aflatoxin-producing moulds.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Aflatoxins are potent carcinogenic chemicals produced by moulds such as *Aspergillus flavus* and *Aspergillus parasiticus*.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] The mould contamination may occur from soil, previously infested almonds, and almond pests such as navel-orange worm.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] High levels of mould growth typically appear as grey to black filament-like growth.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] It is unsafe to eat mould-infected tree nuts.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Some countries have strict limits on allowable levels of aflatoxin contamination of almonds and require adequate testing before the nuts can be marketed to their citizens.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] The European Union, for example, introduced a requirement since 2007 that all almond shipments to the EU be tested for aflatoxin.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] If aflatoxin does not meet the strict safety regulations, either the entire consignment must be reprocessed to eliminate the aflatoxin or it must be destroyed.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] After tracing cases of salmonellosis to almonds, the USDA approved a proposal by the Almond Board of California to pasteurize almonds sold to the public.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] After publishing the rule in March 2007, the almond pasteurization program became mandatory for California companies effective 1 September 2007.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Raw, untreated California almonds have not been commercially available in the U.S. since then.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] California almonds labelled "raw" must be steam-pasteurized or chemically treated with propylene oxide (PPO).
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] This does not apply to imported almonds or almonds sold from the grower directly to the consumer in small quantities.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] The Almond Board of California states: "PPO residue dissipates after treatment".
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Environmental Protection Agency has reported: "Propylene oxide has been detected in fumigated food products; consumption of contaminated food is another possible route of exposure".
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] PPO is classified as Group 2B ("possibly carcinogenic to humans").
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] The USDA-approved marketing order was challenged in court by organic farmers organized by the Cornucopia Institute, a Wisconsin-based farm policy research group which filed a lawsuit in September 2008.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] According to the institute, this almond marketing order has imposed significant financial burdens on small-scale and organic growers and damaged domestic almond markets.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] A federal judge dismissed the lawsuit in early 2009 on procedural grounds.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] In August 2010, a federal appeals court ruled that the farmers have a right to appeal the USDA regulation.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] In March 2013, the court vacated the suit on the basis that the objections should have been raised in 2007 when the regulation was first proposed.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Almonds are 4% water, 22% carbohydrates, 21% protein, and 50% fat (table).
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Per 100 g, almonds contain dietary fiber (12 g), the monounsaturated fat, oleic acid (31 g), and the polyunsaturated fat, linoleic acid (12 g; table source).
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Typical of nuts and seeds, almonds are a source of phytosterols, such as beta-sitosterol.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Almonds are included as a good source of protein among recommended healthy foods by the USDA.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] A 2016 review of clinical research indicated that regular consumption of almonds may reduce the risk of heart disease by lowering blood levels of LDL cholesterol.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] While the almond is often eaten on its own, raw or toasted, it is also a component of various dishes.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Almonds are available in many forms, such as whole, slivered, and ground into flour.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Almond pieces around 2–3 millimetres (1⁄16–1⁄8 in) in size, called "nibs", are used for special purposes such as decoration.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] A wide range of classic sweets feature almonds as a central ingredient.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Marzipan was developed in the Middle Ages.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Since the 19th century almonds have been used to make bread, almond butter, cakes and puddings, candied confections, almond cream-filled pastries, nougat, cookies (macaroons, biscotti and qurabiya), and cakes (financiers, Esterházy torte), and other sweets and desserts.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] In Saudi Arabia, almonds are a typical embellishment for the rice dish kabsa.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Spanish cookery uses almonds in sweet dishes as well as in savory ones, ground up to thicken sauces and stews.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Almonds can be processed into a milk substitute called almond milk; the nut's soft texture, mild flavour, and light colouring (when skinned) make for an efficient analog to dairy, and a soy-free choice for lactose intolerant people and vegans.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Raw, blanched, and lightly toasted almonds work well for different production techniques, some of which are similar to that of soy milk and some of which use no heat, resulting in raw milk.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Almond milk, along with almond butter and almond oil, are versatile products used in both sweet and savoury dishes.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] In Moroccan cuisine, sharbat billooz, a common beverage, is made by blending blanched almonds with milk, sugar and other flavourings.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Almond flour or ground almond meal combined with sugar or honey as marzipan is often used as a gluten-free alternative to wheat flour in cooking and baking.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Almonds contain polyphenols in their skins consisting of flavonols, flavan-3-ols, hydroxybenzoic acids and flavanones analogous to those of certain fruits and vegetables.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] These phenolic compounds and almond skin prebiotic dietary fibre have commercial interest as food additives or dietary supplements.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Historically, almond syrup was an emulsion of sweet and bitter almonds, usually made with barley syrup (orgeat syrup) or in a syrup of orange flower water and sugar, often flavoured with a synthetic aroma of almonds.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Orgeat syrup is an important ingredient in the Mai Tai and many other Tiki drinks.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Due to the cyanide found in bitter almonds, modern syrups generally are produced only from sweet almonds.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Such syrup products do not contain significant levels of hydrocyanic acid, so are generally considered safe for human consumption.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Almonds are a rich source of oil, with 50% of kernel dry mass as fat (whole almond nutrition table).
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] In relation to total dry mass of the kernel, almond oil contains 32% monounsaturated oleic acid (an omega-9 fatty acid), 13% linoleic acid (a polyunsaturated omega-6 essential fatty acid), and 10% saturated fatty acid (mainly as palmitic acid).
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Linolenic acid, a polyunsaturated omega-3 fat, is not present (table).
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] When almond oil is analyzed separately and expressed per 100 grams as a reference mass, the oil provides 3,700 kJ (884 kcal) of food energy, 8 grams of saturated fat (81% of which is palmitic acid), 70 grams of oleic acid, and 17 grams of linoleic acid (oil table).
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] The almond is highly revered in some cultures.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] In the Bible, the almond is mentioned ten times, beginning with Genesis 43:11, where it is described as "among the best of fruits".
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] In Numbers 17, Levi is chosen from the other tribes of Israel by Aaron's rod, which brought forth almond flowers.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] In Jeremiah 1:11–12, the vision of an almond branch conveys a wordplay in Hebrew between *shaqed* (almond) and *shoqed* (watching), symbolizing God's vigilant commitment to fulfill His word.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Many Sephardic Jews give five almonds to each guest before special occasions like weddings.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] Similarly, Christian symbolism often uses almond branches as a symbol of the virgin birth of Jesus; paintings and icons often include almond-shaped haloes encircling the Christ Child and as a symbol of Mary.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] The word "luz", which appears in Genesis 30:37, sometimes translated as "hazel", may actually be derived from the Aramaic name for almond (Luz), and is translated as such in the New International Version and other versions of the Bible.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/almond] The Entrance of the flower (*La entrada de la flor*) is an event celebrated on 1 February in Torrent, Spain, in which the clavarios and members of the Confrerie of the Mother of God deliver a branch of the first-blooming almond-tree to the Virgin.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-araucana] It is also the national tree of Chile and of the neighboring Argentine province of Neuquén.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-araucana] The IUCN changed its conservation status to Endangered in 2013, because logging, forest fires, and grazing have caused its population to dwindle.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-araucana] The leaves are thick, tough, and scale-like, triangular, 3–4 cm (1+1⁄4–1+1⁄2 in) long, 1–3 cm (1⁄2–1+1⁄4 in) broad at the base, and with sharp edges and tips.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-araucana] According to Lusk (2001), the leaves remain attached and stay live for up to 24 years and so cover almost all of the tree, except for the older branches.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-araucana] It is usually dioecious, with the male and female cones on separate trees, though occasional individuals bear cones of both sexes.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-araucana] The male (pollen) cones are oblong and cucumber-shaped, 4 cm (1+1⁄2 in) long at first, expanding to 8–12 cm (3–4+1⁄2 in) long by 5–6 cm (2–2+1⁄2 in) broad at pollen release.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-araucana] The female (seed) cones, which mature in autumn about 18 months after pollination, are globose, large, 12–20 cm (4+1⁄2–8 in) diameter, and hold about 200 seeds.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-araucana] The cones disintegrate at maturity to release the 3–4 cm (1+1⁄4–1+1⁄2 in) long nut-like seeds.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-araucana] The thick bark of *Araucaria araucana*, up to 15 cm thick, may be an adaptation to wildfire.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-araucana] The nearest extant relative is *Araucaria angustifolia*, a South American *Araucaria* from Brazil and northeastern Argentina, which differs in the narrower leaves and shorter bract spines on the seed cones.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-araucana] Members of other sections of the genus *Araucaria* occur in Pacific Islands and in Australia, and include *Araucaria cunninghamii*, *Araucaria heterophylla*, and *Araucaria bidwillii*.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-araucana] The tree's native habitat is the lower slopes of the Chilean and Argentine south-central Andes, approximately between 1,000 m (3,300 ft) and 1,700 m (5,600 ft).
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-araucana] In the Chilean Coast Range *A. araucana* can be found as far south as Villa Las Araucarias (latitude 38°30' S) at an altitude of 640 m amsl.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-araucana] Juvenile trees exhibit a broadly pyramidal or conical habit which naturally develops into the distinctive umbrella form of mature specimens as the tree ages.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-araucana] It prefers well-drained, slightly acidic, volcanic soil, but will tolerate almost any soil type provided it drains well.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-araucana] Seedlings are often not competitive enough to survive unless grown in a canopy gap or exposed isolated area.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-araucana] It is almost never found together with *Chusquea culeou*, *Nothofagus dombeyi*, and *Nothofagus pumilio*, because they typically outcompete *A. araucana*.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-araucana] Logging, long a major threat, was finally banned in 1990.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-araucana] Large fires burned thousands of acres of Araucaria forest in 2001–2002, and areas of national parks have also burned, destroying trees over 1300 years old.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-araucana] Overgrazing and invasive trees are also threats.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-araucana] Extensive human harvesting of piñones (*Araucaria* seeds) can prevent new trees from growing.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-araucana] A Global Trees campaign project that planted 2000trees found a 90 percent 10 year survival rate.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-araucana] Another major threat to the survival of *A. araucana*, is the presence of non-native seed eating species, in particular mammals, which have been shown to severely restrict the reproduction of the tree in comparison to native seed eaters.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-araucana] However, it is still unclear as to how large a role these invasive species play in threatening this species of tree.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-araucana] One study in particular found that native species played a larger role in preventing reproduction through seed destruction.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-araucana] However, this may be due to the relatively recent introduction of the selected species, causing their population to be smaller than other invasive species.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-araucana] A study conducted found that cattle ranching by small landowners and larger timber companies within the range of *A. araucana* severely affects regeneration of seedlings.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-araucana] Its seeds (Mapudungun: *ngulliw*, Spanish: *piñones*) are edible, similar to large pine nuts, and are harvested by indigenous peoples in Argentina and Chile.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-araucana] The tree has some potential to be a food crop in other areas in the future, thriving in climates with cool oceanic summers, e.g., western Scotland, where other nut crops do not grow well.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-araucana] A group of six female trees with one male for pollination could yield several thousand seeds per year.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-araucana] Since the cones drop, harvesting is easy.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-araucana] The tree, however, does not yield seeds until it is around 30–40 years old, which discourages investment in planting orchards (although yields at maturity can be immense); once established, individuals can achieve ages beyond 1000years.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-araucana] Pest losses to rodents and feral pigs limits the yield for human consumption and forage fattening of livestock by *A. araucana* mast.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-araucana] The tree has a high degree of inter-year variability in mast volume, and this variation is synchronous within a given area.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-araucana] This evolved to take advantage of predator satiety.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-araucana] Once valued because of its long, straight trunk, its current rarity and vulnerable status mean its wood is now rarely used; it is also sacred to some indigenous Mapuche.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-araucana] Timber from these trees was used for railway sleepers to access many industrial areas around the port of Chile.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-araucana] Before the tree became protected by law in 1990, some timber mills in Araucanía Region specialised in its wood because its durability and resistance to decay meant it was excellent for making wood products such as veneers and plywood.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-araucana] The species is protected under Appendix I of the Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species (CITES) meaning international trade (including in parts and derivatives) is regulated by the CITES permitting system and commercial trade in wild sourced specimens is prohibited.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-araucana] Many young specimens and seeds were brought or sent back to the England by William Lobb in the 19th century.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-araucana] While in Chile, he collected thousands of seeds of *Araucaria araucana* from the Araucanía Region while working for Veitch Nurseries, which is based in Exeter, England.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-araucana] First identified by Europeans in Chile in the 1780s, it was named *Pinus araucana* by J.I.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-araucana] In 1789, de Jussieu described a new genus called *Araucaria* based on the species, and in 1797, Pavón published a new description of the species which he called *Araucaria imbricata* (an illegitimate name, as it did not use Molina's older species epithet).
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-araucana] Finally, in 1873, after several further redescriptions, Koch published the combination *Araucaria araucana*, validating Molina's species epithet in the genus.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-araucana] They believe the *pewen* was given by a deity or *gwenachen* to nourish their offspring; many *pewen* gathering festivals (*ngillatun*) are celebrated in both Chile and Argentina in gratitude to the tree's sustenance.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-araucana] The origin of the popular English language name "monkey puzzle" lies in its early cultivation in Britain c.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-araucana] 1850, when the species was still very rare in gardens and not widely known.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-araucana] Sir William Molesworth, the owner of a young specimen at Pencarrow garden near Bodmin, Cornwall, was showing it to a group of friends when one of them, the lawyer Charles Austin, remarked *"It would puzzle a monkey to climb that"*.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-araucana] As the species had no existing popular name, first "monkey puzzler" then "monkey puzzle" stuck.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-araucana] As of 1996 Pencarrow had an avenue of mature monkey puzzles.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] The leaves are small and rigid with a sharp tip which can easily penetrate the skin.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] They are narrowly triangular, broad at the base and sessile (without a stem).
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] They measure up to 5 cm (2.0 in) long by 1 cm (0.4 in) wide with fine longitudinal venation, glossy green above and paler underneath.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] The leaf arrangement is both distichous and decussate (referred to as secondarily distichous) – that is, one pair of leaves are produced on the twig opposite each other, and the next pair above is rotated around the twig 90° to them, and so on.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] The cones are terminal, the male (or pollen) cone is a spike up to 20 cm (7.9 in) long which matures around October to November.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] The female (or seed) cone is much larger, reaching up to 30 cm (12 in) long and 20 cm (7.9 in) wide, which is roughly equivalent to a rugby ball.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] At maturity, which occurs from December through to March, female cones are green with 50–100 pointed segments, each of which encloses a seed, and they can weigh up to 10 kg.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] Both seed and pollen cones are some of the largest of all conifer species.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] The edible seeds, known as bunya nuts, measure between 2.5 cm (1.0 in) and 5 cm (2.0 in) long and are ovoid to long-elliptic.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] In the 1970s, botanists Hallé, Oldeman and Tomlinson studied the growth patterns of tropical trees and described a set of 23 "architectural models", named after various botanists, which can be seen as different growth strategy to occupy space.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] *Araucaria bidwillii*, like many species from the Araucariaceae family and the fir genus, changes its structural model over time.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] The trees' pollen cones appear in April and mature in September or October.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] The cones require fifteen months to mature, and the cones fall 17 to 18 months after pollination in late January to early March from the coast to the current Bunya Mountains.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] When there is heavy rainfall or drought, pollination may vary.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] The species was described by the English botanist William Jackson Hooker in 1843, based on material collected in the "Mount Brisbane range of hills, 70 miles N.W. of Moreton Bay" by John Carne Bidwill in 1842.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] The genus name *Araucaria* is taken from the Spanish word *Araucanía*, the name of the area in Chile where the first species of this genus originated, and/or *Araucanos*, the Spanish word for the original inhabitants of the area.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] Hooker coined the species epithet in honour of Bidwill, for his efforts in collecting specimens and bringing them to him.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] In various Australian Aboriginal languages, this tree is known as *banya* (anglicised as *bunya*), *bonye, bon-yi* (in Gubbi Gubbi), *bunyi* or *bunya-bunya*, leading to its common name 'bunya pine'.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] It is also less-known as the false monkey puzzle tree (not to be confused with *Araucaria araucana*, the monkey puzzle tree).
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] The bunya pine is a member of the Section *Bunya* of the genus *Araucaria*, and is the sole extant species within it.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] Two more natural, but very small and very isolated, populations of the species occur approximately 1,500 km (930 mi) to the north, in the wet tropics region of northeastern Queensland – one close to Cannabullen Falls on the Atherton Tableland, and the other in the Mount Lewis National Park.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] Today, the southeast Queensland populations exist as very small groves or single trees in its former range, except on and near the Bunya Mountains, where it is still fairly prolific, while the populations in north Queensland remain stable.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] The limited distribution of *A. bidwillii* in Australia is in part due to poor seed dispersal, and also the drying out of the Australian continent over the millennia, leading to a reduction of areas with suitable climatic zones for rainforest.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] A variety of birds and animals, including sulphur-crested cockatoos (*Cacatua galerita*), short-eared possums (*Trichosurus caninus*), fawn-footed melomys (*Melomys cervinipes*), and wallabies are known to eat the seeds.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] The cockatoos are also a dispersal agent as they will carry seeds to a distant perch to eat, but may drop them on the way.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] The suggestion that extinct large animals (initially dinosaurs and later the Australian megafauna) may have been dispersers for the bunya is reasonable, given the size of the seeds and their energy content, but difficult to confirm given the incompleteness of the fossil record for coprolites.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] A problem in small forestry plantations of the bunya pine in Southeast Queensland is the introduction of red deer (*Cervus elaphus*).
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] Unlike possums and rodents, the deer eat bunya cones while still intact, preventing their dispersal.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] The *bunya*, *bonye*, *bunyi*, *bunya-bunya* or *banya* tree produces edible kernels.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] Each segment contains a kernel in a tough protective shell, which will split when boiled or put in a fire.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] The flavour of the kernel is often compared to a chestnut, although it is less intense in terms of aroma and flavour.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] The savory flavour and aroma is also comparable to cooked potato.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] The cones were a very important food source for native Australians – each Aboriginal family would own a group of trees and these would be passed down from generation to generation.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] This is said to be the only case of hereditary personal property owned by the Aboriginal people.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] After the cones had fallen and the fruit was ripe, a large festival harvest would sometimes occur, between two and seven years apart.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] The people of the region would set aside differences and gather in the Bon-yi Mountains (Bunya Mountains) to feast on the kernels.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] The local people, who were bound by custodial obligations and rights, sent out messengers to invite people from hundreds of kilometres to meet at specific sites.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] The meetings involved Aboriginal ceremonies, dispute settlements and fights, marriage arrangements and the trading of goods.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] In what was probably Australia's largest Indigenous event, diverse tribes – up to thousands of people – once travelled great distances (from as far as Charleville, Bundaberg, Dubbo and Grafton) to the gatherings.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] They stayed for months, to celebrate and feast on the bunya nut.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] The bunya gatherings were an armistice accompanied by much trade exchange, and discussions and negotiations over marriage and regional issues.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] Due to the sacred status of the bunyas, some tribes would not camp amongst these trees.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] Also in some regions, the tree was never to be cut.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] Representatives of many different groups from across southern Queensland and northern New South Wales would meet to discuss important issues relating to the environment, social relationships, politics and The Dreaming lore, feasting and sharing dance ceremonies.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] Many conflicts would be settled at this event, and consequences for breaches of laws were discussed.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] A Bunya festival was recorded by Thomas Petrie (1831–1910), who went with the Aboriginal people of Brisbane at the age of 14 to the festival at the Bunya Range (now the Blackall Range in the hinterland area of the Sunshine Coast).
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] His daughter, Constance Petrie, put down his stories in which he said that the trees fruited at three-year intervals.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] The three-year interval may not be correct.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] Ludwig Leichhardt wrote in 1844 of his expedition to the Bunya feast.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] In 1842, the government of what was then the Colony of New South Wales published a notice in the N.S.W.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] Government Gazette which prohibited settlers from occupying land or cutting timber within a proclaimed "Bunya district".
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] This may have been in recognition of the local Aboriginal people's close association with these trees, or their "fierce protection" of them.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] Regardless, the proclamation was repealed in 1860 in one of the first acts of the government of the newly created Colony of Queensland.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] The Aboriginal people were eventually driven out of the forests and the festivals ceased.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] The forests were felled for timber and cleared to make way for cultivation.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] Indigenous groups such as the Wakawaka, Githabul, Kabi Kabi, Jarowair, Goreng goreng, Butchulla, Quandamooka, Baruŋgam, Yiman and Wulili have continued cultural and spiritual connections to the Bunya Mountains to this day.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] A number of strategies including the use of traditional ecological knowledge have been incorporated into the current management practices of the national park and conservation reserves with the Bunya Murri Ranger project currently operating in the mountains.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] Indigenous Australians eat the nut of the bunya tree (known as *yenggi* Aboriginal pronunciation: [jeŋgi]) both raw and cooked, and also in its immature form.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] Traditionally, the nuts were additionally ground and made into a paste, which was eaten directly or cooked in hot coals to make bread called *manu*.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] The nuts were also stored in the mud of running creeks, and eaten in a fermented state.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] Apart from consuming the nuts, Indigenous Australians ate bunya shoots, and utilised the tree's bark as kindling.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] Bunya nuts are still sold as a regular food item in grocery stalls and street-side stalls around rural southern Queensland.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] Some farmers in the Wide Bay/ Sunshine Coast regions have experimented with growing bunya trees commercially for their nuts and timber.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] The bunya nut has become popularised as a 'bushfood' by indigenous foods enthusiasts.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] A huge variety of home-invented recipes now exists for the bunya nut; from pancakes, biscuits and breads, to casseroles, to 'bunya nut pesto' or hoummus.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] The nut is considered nutritious, with a unique flavour similar to starchy potato and chestnut.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] When the nuts are boiled in water, the water turns red, making a flavoursome tea.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] The nutritional content of the bunya nut is: 40% water, 40% complex carbohydrates, 9% protein, 2% fat, 0.2% potassium, 0.06% magnesium.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] It is also gluten free, making bunya nut flour a substitute for people with gluten intolerance.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] Bunya timber was and is still highly valued as "tonewood" for stringed instruments' sound boards since the first European settlers.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] Since the mid-1990s, the Australian company Maton has used bunya for the soundboards of its BG808CL Performer acoustic guitars.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] The Cole Clark company (also Australian) uses bunya for the majority of its acoustic guitar soundboards.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] The timber is valued by cabinet makers and woodworkers, and has been used for that purpose for over a century.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] A set of 12 seeds sown in Melbourne took an average of about six months to germinate (with the first germinating in three months) and only developed roots after one year.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] The first leaves form a rosette and are dark brown.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] The leaves only turn green once the first stem branch occurs.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] Unlike the mature leaves, the young leaves are relatively soft.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] As the leaves age they become very hard and sharp.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] Cuttings can be successful, though they must be taken from erect growing shoots, as cuttings from side shoots will not grow upright.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] In the highly variable Australian climate, the varied timing of emergence of the seedlings maximises the possibility of at least successful replacement of the parent tree.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] A test of germination was carried out by Smith starting in 1999.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] Seeds were extracted from two mature cones collected from the same tree, a cultivated specimen at Petrie, just north of Brisbane (originally the homestead of Thomas Petrie, the son of the first European to report the species).
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] One hundred apparently full seeds were selected and planted into 30 cm by 12 cm plastic tubes commercially filled with sterile potting mix in early February 1999.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] These were then placed in a shaded area and watered weekly.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] Four tubes were lost due to being knocked over.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] Of a total of 100 seeds placed, 87 germinated.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] The tubes were checked monthly for emergence over three years.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] Of these seeds, 55 emerged from April to December 1999; 32 emerged from January to September in 2000, one seed emerged in January 2001, and the last appeared in February 2001.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] They will reach a height of 35 to 40 metres, and live for about 500 years.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] The cones of the bunya pine are some of the largest produced by the conifer family.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] The cones—which can grow to as much as 35 centimetres (14 in) in diameter when mature, and weigh up to 10 kilograms (22 lb)—can drop on unsuspecting passersby from heights of 40 metres (130 ft) or more.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] The falling cones are capable of causing severe injuries.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] Caution is also advised when parking under these trees as the falling cones can damage vehicles.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] A specimen of *Araucaria bidwillii* in East Los Angeles, California, is featured in Taylor Hackford's 1993 film *Blood In Blood Out* as a touchstone for the main characters.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] The tree, known as "El Pino" ("the pine" in Spanish), has become famous from this association, and is visited by international fans of the film.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria-bidwillii] A late-2020 prank claiming the tree would be cut down incited a brief panic locally.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria] The genus is familiar to many people as the genus of the distinctive Chilean pine or monkey-puzzle tree (*Araucaria araucana*).
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria] No distinct vernacular name exists for the genus.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria] Many are called "pine", although they are only distantly related to true pines, in the genus *Pinus*.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria] The two South American species *A. angustifolia* and *A. araucana* are mostly dioecious, with male and female cones found on separate trees.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria] The other species in the genus are monoecious.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria] The female cones, on the top of the tree, are globose, and vary in size among species from 7 to 25 centimetres (3 to 10 in) in diameter.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria] They contain 80–200 large edible seeds, similar to pine nuts, though larger.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria] The male cones are smaller, 4–10 cm (1+1⁄2–4 in) long, narrow to broad cylindrical, and 1.5–5 cm (1⁄2–2 in) broad.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria] Some Mapuche living in the Andes name themselves Pewenche ("people of the **pewen**") as they traditionally harvested the seeds extensively for food.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria] There are four extant sections and two extinct sections in the genus, sometimes treated as separate genera.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria] Genetic studies indicate that the extant members of the genus can be subdivided into two large clades – the first consisting of the sections *Araucaria*, *Bunya*, and *Intermedia*; and the second of the strongly monophyletic section *Eutacta*.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria] Sections *Eutacta* and *Bunya* are both the oldest taxa of the genus, with *Eutacta* possibly older.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria] Members of *Araucaria* are found in Argentina, Brazil, New Caledonia, Norfolk Island, Australia, New Guinea, Chile and Papua (Indonesia).
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria] Many if not all current populations are relicts, and of restricted distribution.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria] They are found in forest and maquis shrubland, with an affinity for exposed sites.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria] The earliest records of the genus date to the Middle Jurassic, represented by *Araucaria mirabilis* of Argentina, and *Araucaria sphaerocarpa* from England.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria] Fossil records show that the genus also formerly occurred in the northern hemisphere until the end of the Cretaceous period.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria] A possible species of Araucaria may have existed in New Zealand as recently as 350,000 years ago.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria] However, it is also possible that this fossil actually represents a specimen of Agathis.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria] By far the greatest diversity exists in New Caledonia, likely due to a relatively recent adaptive radiation, as all New Caledonian species are more closely related to each other than they are to other *Araucaria*.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria] Much of New Caledonia is composed of ultramafic rock with serpentine soils, with low levels of nutrients, but high levels of metals such as nickel.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria] Consequently, its endemic *Araucaria* species are adapted to these conditions, and many species have been severely affected by nickel mining in New Caledonia and are now considered threatened or endangered, due to their habitat lying in prime areas for nickel mining activities.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria] Some evidence suggests that the long necks of sauropod dinosaurs may have evolved specifically to browse the foliage of tall trees, including those of *Araucaria*.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria] An analysis of modern *Araucaria* leaves found that they have a high energy content but are slow fermenting, making their ancestors a likely attractive target.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria] Some of the species are relatively common in cultivation because of their distinctive, formal symmetrical growth habit.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria] Several species are economically important for timber production.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria] In South America *Araucaria* nuts or seeds are called *piñas* or *piñones* in Spanish and *pinhões* in Portuguese, like pine nuts in Europe.
[src:araucaria-bidwillii/araucaria] Pharmacological reports on the genus *Araucaria* are anti-ulcer, antiviral, neuro-protective, anti-depressant and anti-coagulant.
